Date: 1-16 (1998)  February 1996; revised February 1997.  
Abstract: This paper proposes a 3-dimensional visibility representation of graphs G = (V; E) in which vertices are mapped to rectangles floating in R 3 parallel to the x; y-plane, with edges represented by vertical lines of sight. We apply an extension of the Erd-os-Szekeres Theorem in a geometric setting to obtain an upper bound of n = 56 for the largest representable complete graph K n . On the other hand, we show by construction that n 22. These are the best existing bounds. We also note that planar graphs and complete bipartite graphs K m;n are representable, but that the family of representable graphs is not closed under graph minors. Research on this paper was supported by FCAR, NSERC, NSF, and DFG. 
